<font color="#FF0000">COMMUNISM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Feb 28  5:35:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
People have used an infinite number of defintions of the word &quot;Communism&quot;. The original meaning was &quot;communal&quot;, meaing a purely egalitarian fair society, where everyone is equal, like a stone-age tribe of hunter-gatherers. The reason Lenin used the word Communism is being he was trying to invoke the image of what Marx used the word to mean. Lenin lied and said that he was going to establish a Communist country, refering to the orginal meaning, and then established a brutal dictatorship. Later the word Communist was used to refer to a command economy, in which the economy is centrally controlled instead up being left to it's own devices. The definition of the word Communist used by the American government was &quot;allied with the Soviet Union&quot;. This had absolutely nothing to do with a country's political or economic system. We automatically reflexsively against the Soviet Union just because it was the other superpower, for the same reason Britain had been against France. Both superpowers wanted to control as a large fraction of the Earth as possible. Therefore we were against the Soviet Union and all countries allied with it. Any country allied with the Soviet Union would have the word &quot;Communist&quot; bestowed upon it. A brutal dictatorship allied with the United States would not. Often we would pretend that dictatorships were democratic, if they happened to be allied with us. The defintion of the word &quot;Communism&quot; used by the average American was an undefined amorphous evil thing, the thing that we're against. They didn't really have a definition. They couldn't define it if you asked them. Their only definition was &quot;the thing that we're against&quot;. Tanker is apparently among these people. In the Soviet Union, the word &quot;capitalism&quot; was used in the same way. The United States should have been against dictatorships of all sorts, regardless of whether they happened to be allied with the Soviet Union. We should have been against, not the word &quot;Communism&quot;, but all tyranny, oppression, and human suffering. Of course, we never gave a damn about people suffering elsewhere in the world. Read my previous posts if you doubt that. Hitler killed many more people than Stalin, yet Tanker says that Communism is worse than Facism? Is the slaughter in Rwada not as bad as what the Viet Cong did, because nobody attached the word &quot;Communist&quot; to either side? It is not relevant whether the word &quot;Communist&quot; has been attached to a country or a group of people. What's relevant is what they do, the actions they take, whether they violate human rights, the number of people they kill, etc.
